<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-014-016 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 504 740</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDGE: Work-Group Computing Report  Nov 11 1991 v2 n77 p27(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EDGE Publishing 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Capital gains/formation: AEA endorses the Enterprise CapitalFormation Act. (American Electronics Association)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     LobbyingTax LawElectronic IndustryLegislationPolitical IssuesTrade and professional associationsUnited States. CongressAmerican Electronics Association.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>The American Electronics Association (AEA) has strongly endorsed theEnterprise Capital Formation Act, a targeted capital gains tax cut which wasintroduced in the House and Senate last Thursday.andM;&quot;The Enterprise Capital Formation Act is a creative new approach to capitalgains that will encourage long-term investment in small companies,&quot; said J.andO;Richard Iverson, president and chief executive officer of AEA.andP;  &quot;Today'ssmall entrepreneur cannot attract the long-term investment needed to bringideas to the market.andP;  The situation is devasting for the industry, which ishemorrhaging jobs and market share.&quot;andM;The Enterprise Capital Formation Act would encourage investment in smallcompanies by providing a 50 percent tax deduction for investors who havegains on the corporate stock of companies with less than $100 million inpaid-in capital.andP;  It has a minimum five-year holding period and providesspecial benefits for seed capital investments.andP;  The Act has over 70co-sponsors.andM;&quot;The high tech industry is committed to creating the highest quality productsand services in the world,&quot; Iverson said.andP;  &quot;But we cannot do it alone.andP;  TheEnterprise Capital Formation Act will encourage entrepreneurship, enhanceresearch and development, and create new jobs.&quot;andO;</TEXT></DOC>